<paragraph blockId="16.[831,1437,1181,1399]" pageId="16" pageNumber="91">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[831,964,1181,1204]" pageId="16" pageNumber="91">Comments:</emphasis>
This species is a member of the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Lobl" baseAuthorityYear="1971" box="[1349,1437,1181,1204]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Baeocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lenta">
<emphasis box="[1349,1437,1181,1204]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="91">B. lenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group. The aedeagal characters, in particular the shape of the wide parameres and the short, strongly inflexed apical process of the median lobe, suggest relationships with 
<taxonomicName authority="(Lobl, 1975)" baseAuthorityName="Lobl" baseAuthorityYear="1975" box="[889,1159,1311,1334]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Baeocera" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="91" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="carinata">
<emphasis box="[889,1011,1311,1334]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="91">B. carinata</emphasis>
(Löbl, 1975)
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingRegion box="[1230,1322,1311,1334]" country="Indonesia" name="Sumatera Utara" pageId="16" pageNumber="91">Sumatra</collectingRegion>
. The sclerotized pieces of the internal sac are, however, distinctive in these two species.
</paragraph>
